First, ***How can we define the value of a company for a purchase?***

To define the total value of a company $(B)$ to another that wants to buy it $(A)$, we calculate $V^{*}_B$, using the following formula:

$$
\begin{equation}
V^{*}_B = V_B + \Delta V   
\end{equation}
$$       
Where: 

$V_B$ is the value of the firm $B$ as a separate company, and; 

$\Delta V$ is the incremental net gain from the acquisition

The value of the firm $B$ refers to its value before the acquisition and can be estimated through the company`s market value. The market value can be calculated by multiplying the stock price by the number of shares outstanding for a specific company. 

$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Market value} = \text{Stock price}\times\text{Shares outstanding}  
\end{equation}
$$   


Therefore, net incremental gain from a merger can be determined by the difference between the value of the combined firm $(V_{AB})$ and the sum of the values of the firms as separate entities $(V_A+V_B)$: 


$$
\begin{equation}
 \Delta V =V_{AB}- (V_A+V_B) 
\end{equation}
$$

Now, ***how can we calculate the value of the firm combined?***

The value of the firm combined $(V_{AB})$ can be estimated using the exchange ratio formula, which is given as follows:
$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Exchange ratio} = \frac{\text{Target share price}}{\text{Acquirer share price}}
\end{equation}
$$

So let's calculate it!
$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Exchange ratio} &= \frac{\$44.52}{\$33.30}\\[10pt]
&=1.34
\end{align*}
$$



The exchange ratio is $1.34$. This means $BQ$ has to issue $1.34$ of its shares for every $1$ share of iReport (the Target it plans to acquire). So, $BQ$ has to exchange a total of $261,300$ shares $(1.34 \times 195,000 \text{ shares})$ of its own. 

Once the merger is completed, $BQ$ will have shares $1,661,000$ of common stock $(1,400,000 + 261,000)$ outstanding.

Let's analyze now what is the effect of the merger on the earnings per share. 
Once the merger is completed, $BQ$ will have $1,661,000$ shares of common stock outstanding. If the earnings of each of the firms remain constant, the merged company will be expected to have earnings available for the common stockholders of $\$5,005,000$ $(\$4,300,000 + \$705,000)$. 

The earnings per share of the merged company therefore should equal approximately $\$3.01$ $\left(\frac{\$5,005,000}{1,661,000 \text{ shares}}\right)$. 

Let's see a summary in Table 3.

$$
\begin{array}{ccc}
  &&&&&&&& \textbf{Earnings per share}
\end{array}
$$
$$
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
 \textbf{Stockholders} & \textbf{Before merger} & \textbf{After merger} \\
\hline BQ & \$ 3.07 & \$ 3.01^{*} \\
 \text{iReport} & \$ 3.62 & \hspace{3pt}\$ 4.03^{**} \\

\end{array}
$$
<center>Table 3. Summary of the Effects on Earnings per Share of a Merger between BQ and iReport.

$$
^*\hspace{5pt} \boxed{\dfrac{\$ 4,300,000+\$ 705,000}{1,400,000+(195,000 \times 1.34)}=3.01}
$$
$$
^{**}\hspace{5pt} \boxed{ \$ 3.01 \times 1.34=4.03}
$$

We can now calculate the **market value of the merged company** by adding the added value (ratio of exchange in market price times acquired company market price) to the bidding company´s market value:

$$\footnotesize{
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Market value}\\ 
\text{of the merged firm}\\ 
V_{AB}
\end{array} 
= 
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Market value}\\ 
\text{of acquirer}\\ 
V_A
\end{array} 
+
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Market value}\\ 
\text{of acquired firm}\\ 
V_B
\end{array}
\times
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Exchange ratio}\\ 
\text{in market price}\\ 

\end{array}
}
$$
By evaluating we have:
$$
\begin{align*}
V_{AB} &=  \$62,328,000 + \$6,493,500 \times 1.79 \\[10pt]
 &=  \$73,951,365

\end{align*}
$$

Therefore, we can say ***the value of $\bold{BQ}$, Inc. after acquiring iReport is $\bold{\$73,951,365}$***.

Finally, the value of iReport to $BQ$ is:
$$
\begin{align*}
V^{*}_B &= V_B + \Delta V \\[10pt]
&= \$6,493,500 + \$5,129,865\\[10pt] 
&= \boxed{\$11,623,365}
\end{align*}
$$

***<span style="color: #4257B2">The total value received by $\bold{BQ}$, Inc. $\bold{(A)}$ as a result of buying iReport Publications $\bold{(B)}$ is $\bold{\$11,623,365}$***</span>.

Therefore, $\Delta V$ can is determined as follows:
$$
\begin{align*}
\Delta V &=\$73,951,365-(\$62,328,000+\$6,493,500)\\
&= \boxed{\$5,129,865}
\end{align*}
$$

***<span style="color: #4257B2">The incremental gain of the acquisition is$\bold{\$5,129,865}$***</span>.

Let's recall, ***how can we calculate the Net Present Value $\bold{\operatorname{NPV}}$ of a merger?***

The $\operatorname{NPV}$ of the merger is: 
$$
\begin{equation}
\operatorname{NPV} = V^{*}_B − \text{Cost to Firm $A$ of the acquisition}
\end{equation}
$$
The Value of $B$ company (iReport) to acquiring company $(BQ)$ $V^{*}_B$, has been calculated in section **a.** resulting in a value of $\$11,623,365$. 

The Cost to the firm $A$ of the acquisition has been calculated considering a cash acquisition by paying $\$38$ for each share of iReport. 

If iReport owns $195,000$ shares, then the Cost to firm $A$ of the acquisition is $\$7,410,000$ $(195,000 \text{ shares} \times \$38)$.

Finally, the $\operatorname{NPV}$ can be calculated by evaluating into formula $(7)$ the previous values:


$$
\begin{align*}
\operatorname{NPV} &= V^{*}_B − \text{Cost to Firm $A$ of the acquisition}\\[10pt]
&=\$11,623,365 − \$7,410,000\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\$4,213,365}
\end{align*}
$$


***<span style="color: #4257B2">The NPV of the acquisition, if $\bold{BQ}$ offers $\bold{\$38}$ per share to iReport, is $\bold{\$4,213,365}$</span>***.

So let's find the value of the **price per share** that solves the previous equation by using the formula $(7)$ from part **c.**:

$$
\begin{align*}
0=\operatorname{NPV}&= V^{*}_B − \text{Cost to Firm $A$ of the acquisition}\\[10pt]
&= V^{*}_B − \text{Shares outstanding} \times \text{Price per share}\\[10pt]
0 &= \$11,623,365 – 195,000 \times \text{Price per share}\\[10pt]
\text{Price per share} &= \frac{\$11,623,365}{195,000}\\[10pt]
\text{Price per share} &= \boxed{\$59.607}
\end{align*}
$$

Let's check our result by recalculating $\operatorname{NPV}$ using this value for the stock price:

$$
\begin{align*}
\operatorname{NPV}
&= \$11,623,365\hspace{5pt} – \hspace{5pt}195,000 \times \$59.607\\[10pt]
&= \$11,623,365 - \$11,623,365\\[10pt]
&= 0
\end{align*}
$$

So, ***<span style="color: #4257B2">the maximum price that the acquirer firm is willing to pay in cash per share of the target firm is $\bold{\$59.607}$</span>***.
